# Append-only: nothing on disk mutates

Once a blob is written, it is never rewritten. Once a ledger event file is written, it is never modified. Every on-disk artifact is append-only at the file-creation level.

Edits do not mutate an existing kino; they create a new version — a new blob, a new event file — that declares the previous version as a parent. The old version is still fully present on disk. v1 and v5 sit side by side as equals; neither is buried.

The consequences are worth stating plainly:

- **Full history is free.** There is no "check git log" step to see past states — every version is a first-class object right where it was written.
- **There are no merge conflicts inside Kinora's own files.** The files are immutable; concurrent writes from different branches always produce disjoint paths.
- **Concurrent agent writes do not race.** Two agents that independently decide to edit kino X produce two version events, both valid, and the fork surfaces as multiple heads on the same id. The system never loses one agent's work to satisfy the other.
- **Rollback is a pointer move, not a destructive operation.** "Go back to v2" means resolve-at-version; v3 and v4 still exist, they just are not the current head.

This is how content-addressed storage and an append-only ledger reinforce each other: the store guarantees any content you have seen before is reachable; the ledger guarantees every decision that was ever made is traceable.
